Polyketide biosynthetic systems employ several strategies for the production of structurally diverse polyketides. Among the polyketide biosynthetic enzymes, a growing number of enzymes that catalyze a Michael-type addition have been identiﬁed. These enzymes are responsible for constructing unique polyketide backbone structures, forming heterocycles, and incorporating heteroatoms into the polyketide backbone, all of which contribute to the diversiﬁcation of the polyketide structure. This review summarizes the current understanding of the function of enzymes catalyzing a Michael-type addition in polyketide biosynthesis, with a particular focus on mechanistic

Polyketide synthases (PKSs) synthesize many structurally diverse bioactive polyketide natural products in bacteria, fungi, and plants.1–6 In the PKS-catalyzed reaction, an acyltransferase (AT) domain, a ketosynthase (KS) domain, and a carrier protein (CP) domain constitute the three core domains. The AT domain recognizes a specic acyl starter or extender unit and catalyzes its transfer to the phosphopantetheine arm of CP. The PKS substrate and reaction intermediate are maintained as thioester conjugates of CP. The KS domain catalyzes a Claisen-type condensation of the extender unit to an acyl starter substrate or a growing polyketide chain. The resulting b-keto moiety is processed by ketoreductase (KR), dehydratase (DH), and enoylreductase (ER) domains to yield a b-hydroxy group, an a,b- double bond, or a fully reduced methylene. The reductive step can be partly or fully omitted before the next condensation step, leading to a complex functionalization pattern at the b-position. Additionally, structural modications, such as alkylations, hydroxylations, and heterocyclizations, may occur during poly- ketide chain elongation.7 Finally, the elongated polyketide chain is released from the PKS assembly line, generally via a hydrolysis or macrocyclization catalyzed by the thioesterase (TE) domain.8 The released polyketide intermediates are further modied by tailoring reactions, including hydroxylations, glycosylations, and cyclizations, which are oen crucial for the biological activities of the nal polyketide natural products. PKSs can be classied into various types.1–3 Type I PKSs are large multifunctional enzymes with covalently linked catalytic domains. Modular type I PKSs consist of multiple modules, each of which is basically responsible for a single round of

Modular type I PKSs are further divided into cis-AT PKSs5 and trans-AT PKSs.9–11 Iterative type I PKSs, which comprise only a set of catalytic domains, iteratively elongate a polyketide chain.12,13 Type I PKS modules are oen fused to nonribosomal peptide synthetase (NRPS) modules, forming a PKS–NRPS hybrid.14,15 Type II PKSs consist of a dissociable complex of subunits such as KS, chain-length factor, and CP.16 Type III PKSs are KS homodimers.17 Polyketide biosynthetic systems produce structurally diverse polyketides via several strategies that vary regarding the incor- poration of various starter and extender units, the number of the use of modication reactions condensation reactions, during polyketide chain elongation, the cyclization patterns of the fully elongated polyketide chain, and post-PKS tailoring reactions. Elucidating how polyketide biosynthetic systems diversify their polyketide products is important for identifying the biosynthetic machinery related to unknown polyketide natural products and for engineering metabolic pathways to produce non-natural polyketide compounds. The conjugate addition of an enolate-type carbon nucleo- phile to an a,b-unsaturated carbonyl group (i.e., Michael addi- tion) is one of the most important C–C bond-forming reactions in synthetic organic chemistry (Fig. 1).18–21 Additionally, hetero- Michael additions, such as oxa- and aza-Michael additions, are important for creating C–heteroatom bonds.22–24 The natural product biosynthetic machinery also uses a Michael-type addi- tion to synthesize structurally diverse bioactive compounds. A growing number of enzymes that catalyze a Michael-type addi- tion have been identied in polyketide biosynthetic pathways.

Because Michael-type additions can incorporate C–C bonds and C–heteroatom bonds in positions distinct from those associ- ated with the nucleophilic addition to a carbonyl carbon, enzymes catalyzing a Michael-type addition help generate pol- yketide metabolites with diverse structures. These enzymes are responsible for the construction of a unique polyketide back- bone structure, the formation of a heterocycle, and the incor- poration of a heteroatom into the polyketide backbone. Recent biochemical and structural studies provided detailed mecha- nistic insights into the Michael-type addition and associated reactions. This review will summarize the functions of enzymes catalyzing a Michael-type addition in polyketide biosynthesis as well as the underlying catalytic mechanisms. 2. Michael-type addition for C–C bond formation

Claisen-type condensation plays a central role in the C–C bond- forming reactions associated with polyketide biosynthesis. KSs catalyze the decarboxylative Claisen condensation with a malonyl-type extender unit to elongate a linear polyketide chain.1,6 The incorporation of a substituted malonyl extender unit results in an alkyl branch at the a position in the KS-catalyzed condensation reaction.25–27 Alkylations may also occur at the a and b positions during polyketide chain elongation. The methylation at the a position is catalyzed by the SAM-dependent methyltransferase domain, mostly in bacterial trans-AT PKSs and fungal iterative PKSs.6,12 The b-alkyl branch is oen introduced by an aldol addition of acetyl enolate with the b-ketoacyl-CP cata- lyzed by a 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA synthase homolog, mostly in trans-AT PKS systems.10,28 Additionally, the b-alkyl branch may be introduced through a Michael-type addition to the a,b-unsaturated polyketide intermediate. The Michael addition strategy is responsible for the construction of carbocyclic and heterocyclic rings in the polyketide skeleton and contributes to the structural diversication of polyketide natural products. 2.1 Formation of d-lactone and glutarimide moieties catalyzed by the branching module

The antimitotic phytotoxin rhizoxin produced by the Rhizopus symbiont Burkholderia rhizoxinica has a d-lactone moiety that is introduced by the b-branching of the polyketide backbone.29,30 The d-lactone moiety is essential for the binding of rhizoxin to the b-tubulin subunit, which results in antimitotic activity.31 The polyketide backbone of rhizoxin is constructed by a trans-AT type modular PKS (RhiA–RhiF). RhiE has the branching module comprising KS, branching (B), and CP domains for the formation of the d-lactone moiety (Fig. 2A). A biochemical analysis of the branching module revealed that the d-lactone moiety is generated through an intermolecular Michael-type addition and the following cyclization.32 The CP-bound acetate enolate that is produced by the decarboxylation of a malonyl unit nucleophili- cally attacks the KS-bound a,b-unsaturated thioester. Conse- quently, the KS and CP domains are covalently linked by the branched polyketide intermediate. The rhizoxin branching module can use methylmalonyl-CoA as well as malonyl-CoA in vitro.33 An analysis of the inuence of the d-hydroxy group conguration on the reaction34 indicated that the rhizoxin branching module accepts both the natural S enantiomer and the non-natural R enantiomer. However, the conversion rate of the R enantiomer is signicantly lower than that of the S enantiomer, suggesting that the branching module has a stereochemical substrate preference. In both cases, the syn-substituted lactone is exclusively formed. The conguration of the d-hydroxy group appears to determine the stereochemical course of the reaction.

Branching modules are also encoded by the biosynthetic gene clusters for glutarimide-containing polyketides such as iso- migrastatin, 9-methylstreptimidone (Fig. 2B).35–37 The branching module of glutarimide trans-AT PKS, which consists of KS, unknown (X), and CP domains, is highly similar to that of rhizoxin PKS RhiE, implying that the gluta- rimide moiety is constructed via the same strategy. The CP- bound acetate enolate derived from a malonyl unit nucleophili- cally attacks the KS-bound a,b-unsaturated thioester. The car- boxamide group, which is formed by the amidotransferase domain of the PKS loading module, subsequently attacks the KS- bound thioester to produce the CP-bound glutarimide. The rhi- zoxin branching module can accept a carboxamide analog to generate a glutarimide unit.34 Additionally, the hybrid rhizoxin branching module in which the RhiE B domain is replaced by the X domain of 9-methylstreptimidone PKS produces both gluta- rimide and lactone units from the corresponding acyl units. Thus, the B and X domains seem to be functionally equivalent.38 The crystal structure of the RhiE KS–B di-domain indicates that the KS domain contains a typical thiolase fold and has a Cys3228–His3364–His3404 catalytic triad, similar to canonical This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2018

KS domains (Fig. 3).32 The RhiE KS–B di-domain was used for a mutational analysis because it is impossible to obtain a catalyt- ically active KS domain as a standalone enzyme. The C3228A the KS domain disrupts the chain-branching mutation of activity.32,39 Cys3228 is necessary for the binding of the polyke- tide intermediate. Moreover, His3364 and His3404 mutations also decrease the chain-branching activity. The His3404 residue likely activates the malonyl carboxylate and stabilizes the enolate. Thus, the KS domain active site is crucial for the Michael addition. The B domain adopts a double-hotdog fold similar to that of the DH domain. The B domain contains an Asp residue at the position corresponding to the catalytic Asp residue of the DH domain. However, the mutation of the Asp residue does not inuence the chain-branching activity. Additionally, the substitution of the B domain with the DH domain does not aﬀect the chain-branching activity, suggesting that the B domain does not have any catalytic roles associated with the Michael addition or heterocyclization.38 The B domain might have only a structural role in the branching module. Thus, the KS domain of the branching module alone mediates the Michael addition and the subsequent hetero- cyclization reactions. The KS domain of the branching module is functionally diﬀerent from canonical KS domains, which produce linear polyketide chains through a Claisen-type condensation, although the active site of the branching KS domain is very similar to that of the canonical KS domain. It remains unclear how the branching KS domain evolved. 2.2 Biosynthesis of dialkylresorcinol and stilbene in bacteria Bacterial 2,5-dialkylresorcinols have diverse biological activi- ties.40 Some dialkylresorcinols are used as bacterial signaling molecules.41 The chemical structures of dialkylresorcinols are quite similar to those of the monoalkylresorcinols that are synthesized by type III PKSs. Thus, StlD employs a novel catalytic mechanism for the condensation of two acyl units to produce the CHD scaﬀold. 2.3 Formation of the naphthoquinone moiety in rifamycin biosynthesis Rifamycin B, which is an ansamycin antibiotic produced by Amycolatopsis mediterranei, contains a naphthalenic ring in the polyketide backbone (Fig. 6).50 The rifamycin polyketide back- bone is constructed via the condensation of the 3-amino-5- hydroxybenzoic acid (AHBA) starter unit with malonyl and methylmalonyl extender units in a reaction catalyzed by a cis-AT type modular PKS (RifA–RifE), followed by the formation of a macrolactam catalyzed by the amide synthase RifF. Disruption of the rifF gene leads to the accumulation of a series of linear polyketides ranging from a tetraketide to a decaketide.51,52 The linear tetraketide contains a benzenoid core derived from the AHBA starter unit, while the longer linear polyketides have a naphthoquinone core, suggesting that the formation of the rifamycin naphthalenic ring likely occurs during polyketide chain elongation. 2.5 C-Ribosylation in alnumycin biosynthesis Glycosylation is an important process that modies polyketide natural products. Sugar substituents are oen essential for the biological activity and solubility of natural products.61 The glycosylation of natural products via an O-glycosidic linkage is mostly catalyzed by glycosyltransferases.62,63 In rare cases, enzymes catalyze the formation of a hydrolytically resistant C– glycosidic bond.64–66 The aromatic polyketide alnumycin A contains a unique 40-hydroxy-50-hydroxymethyl-20,70-dioxane unit attached to the prealnumycin aglycone through a C–glycosidic bond (Fig. 8).67,68 The prealnumycin aglycone is produced by a type II PKS and tailoring enzymes.69 The dioxane unit is then introduced through a C-ribosylation and the following modi- cation reactions.69,70 The C-glycosynthase AlnA catalyzes the formation of a C–C bond between D-ribose-5-phosphate and Fig. 8 Reactions of AlnA and AlnB in alnumycin biosynthesis. The structure of AlnA complexed with D-ribose-5-phosphate implies that AlnA binds a linear phosphosugar (Fig. 9). Structural and biochemical data suggest that AlnA catalyzes the Michael-type addition of D-ribose-5- phosphate to the aglycone, followed by a hemi-acetal formation and dehydration (Fig. 8).71 In the initial step, the C20 hydroxy group of the linear phosphosugar intermediate is likely depro- tonated by Glu29 and stabilized by Lys159. The resulting enolate nucleophilically attacks the C8 position of the prealnumycin isochromanequinone aglycone. The generated negative charge at the quinone oxygen in the transition state might be stabilized by Lys86. The importance of Glu29, Lys86, and Lys159 has been conrmed by a mutational analysis. 3. Michael-type addition for C–O bond formation Cyclic ether moieties are frequently detected in polyketide structures.72,73 These moieties can be synthesized by the This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2018 intramolecular nucleophilic addition of a hydroxy group to electrophiles such as an epoxide, carbonyl moiety, and Michael acceptor.73,74 Several enzymes that catalyze an oxa-Michael addition have recently been identied in polyketide biosyn- thetic pathways. The intramolecular oxa-Michael addition can install ve- and six-membered cyclic ethers with various substitution patterns during polyketide chain elongation.

3.1 Pyran synthase domain in the trans-AT PKS system The pyran synthase (PS) domain catalyzes the formation of ve- or six-membered cyclic ethers from an a,b-unsaturated acyl thioester intermediate during the polyketide chain elongation by trans-AT PKSs.75 The PS domain is generally located imme- diately downstream of the DH domain. The PS domain acts on the transiently formed a,b-unsaturated thioester intermediate that is produced by the DH domain before the polyketide chain is transferred to the downstream module.

In pederin biosynthesis, the PS domain (PedPS) catalyzes the formation of a tetrahydropyran ring through the intramolecular oxa-Michael addition of a z-hydroxy group (at C7) to the b posi- tion of a trans-a,b-unsaturated intermediate (Fig. 10A).75,76 In sorangicin biosynthesis, the PS domain (SorPS8) of PKS module 8 catalyzes the formation of a dihydropyran ring via the intra- molecular oxa-Michael addition of a z-hydroxy group to the b position of a trans-a,b/cis-g,d diene intermediate (Fig. 10B).77,78 In misakinolide biosynthesis, the PS domain catalyzes the formation of a dihydropyran ring through the intramolecular oxa-Michael addition of a z-hydroxy group to the b position of a trans-a,b/cis-g,d diene intermediate.79 In these cases, the z- hydroxy group is constructed by a KR domain in the PKS module. These PS domains generate pyran products from both D- and L-z-hydroxy substrates in vitro, suggesting a relaxed specicity for the conguration of the z-hydroxy group.75,78,79 PedPS exhibits a slight preference for the natural L-z-hydroxy substrate over the non-natural D-z-hydroxy substrate.75 In the biosyntheses of oocydin and phormidolide, the PS domain catalyzes the formation of a tetrahydrofuran ring through the intramolecular oxa-Michael addition of an 3-hydroxy group (at C6) to the b position of a trans-a,b-unsaturated thioester inter- mediate (Fig. 10C).80,81 The 3-hydroxy group is installed by a trans-acting monooxygenase. In spliceostatin and thailan- statin NRPS–PKS hybrid systems, the side-chain hydroxy group of a threonine moiety incorporated by NRPS functions as a nucleophile for the intramolecular oxa-Michael addition (Fig. 10D).82–84 The PS domain stereoselectively catalyzes

This residue might deprotonate the hydroxy group to facilitate the oxa-Michael addition and then protonate the a position of the intermediate. 3.2 Dual-function DH domain in the cis-AT PKS system The PS-like domain is not present in cis-AT PKS systems. Instead, the DH domain (AmbDH3) of the cis-AT PKS module is responsible for the tetrahydropyran formation in ambruticin biosynthesis.87,88 An in vitro analysis of AmbDH3 using synthetic substrate analogs revealed that AmbDH3 is a dual-function enzyme.88 It rst catalyzes a dehydration to produce a trans- a,b-unsaturated acyl thioester intermediate and subsequently catalyzes the intramolecular oxa-Michael addition of a z- hydroxy group to form the tetrahydropyran ring (Fig. 12). In the biosynthesis of polyketide natural products, a Michael- type addition is commonly used for constructing unique carbocyclic and heterocyclic rings in the polyketide backbone and for incorporating a heteroatom into the polyketide back- bone. These reactions are frequently important for the biolog- ical activity of the nal polyketide products. As presented, a growing number of polyketide biosynthetic enzymes that catalyze a Michael-type addition have been identied and bio- chemically characterized, providing mechanistic insights into the enzymatic Michael-type addition that occurs during poly- ketide biosynthesis. It is now clear that many types of enzymes can catalyze a Michael-type addition. It should be noted that many enzymes, embedded PKS domains and trans-acting enzymes, catalyze a Michael-type addition during polyketide chain elongation. In this case, the enzymes can use a CP-bound a,b-unsaturated acyl thioester intermediate as a Michael acceptor. The enzymes designed for a Michael-type addition oen resemble the well-characterized PKS enzymes, such as KS, DH, and TE, implying the enzymes are evolutionarily related. Polyketide biosynthetic systems might generate enzymes cata- lyzing a Michael-type addition from canonical PKS enzymes to produce structurally diverse polyketide metabolites. In some cases, the enzymes have dual functions involving the coupling of a Michael-type addition with other reaction (e.g., condensa- tion, dehydration, and hydrolysis) to enable a mechanistically complex reaction. Several recent structural and mutational analyses have facilitated the identication of the catalytic

residues and motifs for a Michael-type addition. However, it remains poorly understood how the enzymes control the face selectivity of a Michael-type addition. Therefore, further biochemical and structural studies are necessary for an increased mechanistic understanding of a Michael-type addi- tion. Enzymes catalyzing a Michael-type addition are powerful tools for the structural diversication of polyketide compounds. Accumulation of knowledge will facilitate rational engineering of polyketide biosynthetic pathways to create new polyketide structures. Genome mining is an eﬀective way to identify new natural products. Considering many uncharacterized polyke- tide biosynthetic gene clusters are now present in databases, the enzymes catalyzing a Michael-type addition described in this review may be useful for elucidating the biosynthetic machinery related to unknown polyketide natural products. 7.
